Police in Makueni have launched investigations into an incident where an elderly man died in a minibus while travelling from Machakos town to Kibwezi in Makueni County on Friday. Henry Musyoka, 65, was discovered dead by the 46 – seater matatu’s conductor when the latter went to his seat number three to collect fare. Makueni county police commander Joseph Ole Napeiyan said the matter was reported to Makueni police station by the same conductor. “It was reported at 1620 hours by one Mr Japheth Mbaluka, Kenyan Male adult and a conductor of PSV motor vehicle registration number KBA 342 N make Mitsubishi FH plying Machakos – Kibwezi route that at about 1525 hours while plying the said route on reaching Wote town, they stopped short at Wote bus stage for passengers to alight,” Ole Napeiyan on Saturday told reporters. “He (the conductor) went to collect the fare from a passenger who was seated on seat number three. On reaching him, he found the deceased couldn’t talk thereby discovering that he wasn’t conscious. The passenger had boarded the vehicle at Machakos Bus Park,” Ole Napeiyan said. Ole Napeiyan said the vehicle was immediately driven to Makueni police station where police took over the scene and found the deceased seated in his seat appearing dead. He said the deceased was then identified as Henry Muthama Musyoka, 65, who hails from the Kathyaka location in the Kibwezi division. “Medical personnel from Makueni Referral Hospital were informed and took part. The cause of the death is not yet established,” he said. The body according to the police boss had no visible physical injuries. Ole Napeiyan said the scene was processed and the body was moved to Makueni Referral Hospital mortuary awaiting autopsy. Inquest file on the incident had been opened at the station.